    {
      "text": "What is the cause of lactational amenorrhea?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Increased progesterone"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Increased GnRH secretion"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Decreased prolactin secretion"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Increased prolactin secretion"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 3,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: D) Increased <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"760a997a7b1692777196db9355b82a\">prolactin</span> secretion</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation: </strong></p>\n\n<p>Elevated <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"760a997a7b1692777196db9355b82a\">prolactin</span> levels during <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4abd8094e51692777191b1eb073735\">lactation</span> lead to <strong>suppression of normal <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3a03cad6c616927771925038b55989\">menstrual</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1dc6654c781692777185d3f1040369\">cycling</span> through <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f087a3103216927771903f59008962\">interference</span> with hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian function</strong>. <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4abd8094e51692777191b1eb073735\">Lactation</span> is a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"6c2c85ae6b16927771950809419a59\">physiological</span> state of <strong>hyperprolactinemia with associated amenorrhea</strong>.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Lactational Amenorrhea:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>During breastfeeding, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"760a997a7b1692777196db9355b82a\">prolactin</span> levels are elevated.</li>\n\t<li>High <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"760a997a7b1692777196db9355b82a\">prolactin</span> levels cause:\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Suppression of GnRH (Gonadotropin-Releasing Hormone) release from the hypothalamus</li>\n\t\t<li>Disruption of the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a2af1612021692777196c7044ee75b\">pulsatile</span> release pattern of GnRH</li>\n\t\t<li>Reduction in LH (Luteinizing Hormone) pulses from the pituitary</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>Without proper LH pulses:\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Ovulation doesn't occur</li>\n\t\t<li>Regular <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3a03cad6c616927771925038b55989\">menstrual</span> cycles don't resume <strong>(amenorrhea)</strong></li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<table align=\"center\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; width:592px\">\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid black; border-left:1px solid black; border-right:1px solid black; border-top:1px solid black; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Hormones that favor milk production</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid black; border-left:none; border-right:1px solid black; border-top:1px solid black; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Hormones that <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"6b3de87b7c16927771901326efbcd2\">inhibit</span> milk production</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid black; border-left:1px solid black; border-right:1px solid black; border-top:none; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Prolactin</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Insulin</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Glucocorticoids</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Growth hormone</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Thyroxine</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid black; border-left:none; border-right:1px solid black; border-top:none; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Estrogen</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Progesterone</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Increased progesterone</strong> <strong>(Option A):</strong> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"183d374ac91692777196c63c850299\">Progesterone</span> levels are low during <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4abd8094e51692777191b1eb073735\">lactation</span> because <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"264a9eb50d1692777194427a13247b\">ovulation</span> does not occur, and no <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7e902103fb16927771857729aade8b\">corpus</span> luteum forms to produce progesterone.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Increased GnRH <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9b0ae3750916927771986c15d4ff4d\">secretion</span> (Option B):</strong> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"760a997a7b1692777196db9355b82a\">Prolactin</span> inhibits GnRH secretion; thus, GnRH levels are decreased, not increased.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Decreased <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"760a997a7b1692777196db9355b82a\">prolactin</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9b0ae3750916927771986c15d4ff4d\">secretion</span> (Option C): </strong>Decreased <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"760a997a7b1692777196db9355b82a\">prolactin</span> would lead to the resumption of GnRH pulsatility, ovulation, and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3a03cad6c616927771925038b55989\">menstrual</span> cycles, which contradicts the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"955afd17541692777195b119746b97\">physiology</span> of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"35ee02af361692777191febf0f1887\">lactational</span> amenorrhea.</p>",
