      "text": "A 26-year-old woman who has had 2 children through normal delivery presents with a dull aching pain over the abdomen, with irregular menses. Per vaginal examination revealed a mass felt through the posterior fornix. A USG showed a clear ovarian cyst of size 5 x 5 cm. What is the next best step?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Measure CA 125 levels"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Follow up after 6 weeks"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Laparoscopy"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "CT pelvis"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 1,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer: B) Follow up after 6 weeks </strong><strong> </strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation: </strong>A clear ovarian <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1405ad7b46169277718580acad7562\">cyst</span> measuring 5 x 5 cm in a reproductive-age woman is likely a <strong>functional ovarian cyst. </strong>The recommended management is observation with a follow-up <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"df077f2c3d16927772019f8223e58f\">ultrasound</span> after<strong> </strong><strong>6 weeks</strong><strong> </strong>to monitor for resolution.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Functional Ovarian Cysts:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Arise from ovarian follicles during <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b0c3f6b8901692777203d0446fe1f4\">follicle</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"76948f718016927771924774ade7e9\">maturation</span> and ovulation.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Types:</strong>\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Single Cysts:</strong> Most common, often a single <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"031a38f17a16927772036476ede2ae\">follicular</span> or <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7e902103fb16927771857729aade8b\">corpus</span> luteum cyst.</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Multiple Cysts:</strong> Can occur in conditions like:\n\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t<li>Polycystic <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7b1a7ff355169277719401475de6fb\">Ovary</span> Syndrome (PCOS)</li>\n\t\t\t<li>Ovarian <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"97cdd1c214169277718992e2918f2c\">Hyperstimulation</span> Syndrome (OHSS)</li>\n\t\t\t<li>FSH-secreting <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b775f0c475169277719593c573f6ff\">pituitary</span> adenomas</li>\n\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><strong>Features:</strong>\n\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Functional cysts are typically 3–7 cm, and those larger than 10 cm or persistent for more than 3 months may require further investigation for malignancy.</li>\n\t\t<li>Related to hormonal variations.</li>\n\t\t<li>Filled with clear fluid (unless <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4642acfc0c16927771880b34fa5174\">hemorrhage</span> occurs).</li>\n\t\t<li>Benign, often asymptomatic</li>\n\t\t<li>Typically resolve on their own</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li><strong>Management:</strong>\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Observation:</strong> Most cysts resolve spontaneously within<strong> 4-6 months.</strong>\n\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t<li><strong>Follow-up: </strong>Regular <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"df077f2c3d16927772019f8223e58f\">ultrasound</span> <strong>after 6-12 weeks</strong> to monitor persistent or enlarging cysts.</li>\n\t\t\t<li><strong>Symptomatic Treatment:</strong> Combined oral contraceptives (COCs) may be prescribed for pain or <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"863f5457381692777190f05632a8b2\">irregular</span> menses.</li>\n\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><strong>Surgery: </strong>Indicated for cysts larger than 10 cm, persistent, or <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"509310d4411692777199f2ffdb7769\">symptomatic</span> (e.g., pain, torsion).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Measure <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7f67a6e93116927771830548deb747\">CA 125</span> levels </strong><strong>(Option A):</strong><strong> </strong>Elevated <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7f67a6e93116927771830548deb747\">CA 125</span> can indicate <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4af6983ff31692777194b80e4a7e57\">ovarian cancer</span> but is often raised in <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1bbae82f1f16927771824f797639fa\">benign</span> conditions like menstruation, endometriosis, or <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7cd6eb19341692777195d83aafdcb3\">pelvic</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9d21dd5d3116927771907405b181bc\">inflammatory</span> disease. It is primarily useful in <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"c9ba8fa63616927771962d84263e40\">postmenopausal</span> women with suspected malignancy.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Laparoscopy</strong><strong> (Option B):</strong><strong> </strong>Immediate surgery is unnecessary for a likely functional cyst. <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"6aea253fe3169277719122813f8e25\">Laparoscopy</span> is considered if the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1405ad7b46169277718580acad7562\">cyst</span> persists, grows, or causes <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4cdc8161f71692777180df58cafa93\">acute</span> symptoms like <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"49c306e91e1692777200be46fecf66\">torsion</span> or rupture.</p>\n\n<p><br />\n<strong>CT <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"c25071fa3816927771955eeaf9d45e\">pelvis</span> </strong><strong>(Option C):</strong> A <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"337d5efcc516927772009422f7ce30\">transvaginal</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"df077f2c3d16927772019f8223e58f\">ultrasound</span> is the preferred <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"fe3220767716927771892419444041\">imaging</span> for ovarian cysts. CT is reserved for detecting and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8ea2e3870f16927771990a138acbc1\">staging</span> suspected ovarian neoplasms, which is not indicated here.</p>",
      "question_images": [],
